run, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lezay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Christophe.  Irish Fitzroy.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or rushing stream, a variant of   Ray  , with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>; or a habitational name from Le Ray, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Ray","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ray</i> or <i>Rey</i>, perhaps a pet form of names beginning in <i>Ray</i> or <i>Rey</i>, especially   Raymond  .","English: nickname from Old French <i>rei</i> ‘king’, denoting someone who behaved in a regal fashion, one with the bearing of a king, or referring to the mock king or lord in festive games and pageants, e.g. at Christmas, May Day, or harvest. Compare   Roy   and   King  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>ræghe</i> (Old English <i>rǣge</i>) ‘female roe deer’ or in northern England more likely northern Middle English <i>rā</i>, <i>raa</i>, <i>rae</i>, <i>ray</i> (Old English <i>rā</i>) ‘roe deer’, perhaps for a timid person or swift runner. Compare   Roe  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume II de Lezay was born about 1051, in Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France as the son of Guillaume Joscelin Lezay. He had at least 1 son with Aenor de Talmond. He died about 1110, at the age of 61."},"et":{"Abt 1051–ABT 1110":"umbes 1051–umbes 1110","1051–1110":"1051–1110","1065–1129":"1065–1129","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1129":"1129","Abt 1051":"umbes 1051","ABT 1110":"umbes 1110","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1051–ABT 1110":"noin 1051–noin 1110","1051–1110":"1051–1110","1065–1129":"1065–1129","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1129":"1129","Abt 1051":"noin 1051","ABT 1110":"noin 1110","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1051–ABT 1110":"environ 1051–environ 1110","1051–1110":"1051–1110","1065–1129":"1065–1129","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1129":"1129","Abt 1051":"environ 1051","ABT 1110":"environ 1110","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lezay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","lifeSummary":"Guillaume II de Lezay est né envi